## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| Framework | **Next.js** (App Router, Server Actions) |
| Language | **TypeScript** |
| UI | **React** with Lucide React icons |
| Styling | **TailwindCSS v4** with `tailwind-merge` + `clsx` |
| CSV Parsing | **PapaParse** |
| HTTP Requests | Node.js native `https` module (for LinkedIn), [fetch](file:///c:/Users/mimod/OneDrive/Desktop/Projects/leads_qualiferV2/src/app/actions/scraper-actions.ts#1314-1398) (for Bright Data API) |
| Google Auth | Manual JWT signing with Node.js `crypto` module — no Google SDK |
| Persistence | Filesystem JSON (`progress/` directory) |

---

## External APIs & Services

| Service | What It's Used For | Auth Method |
|---|---|---|
| **Bright Data — Dataset API** | Activity check (recent posts), profile scraping, web scraping | Bearer API key (`BRIGHT_DATA_API_KEY`) |
| **Bright Data — Proxy** (optional) | Residential proxy for web requests | Proxy URL string |
| **LinkedIn** (direct) | Profile page + contact overlay scraping | `li_at` session cookie from browser |
| **Google Sheets API** | Export qualified leads to a spreadsheet | Service account JWT (base64-encoded credentials) |

### Bright Data Dataset IDs
- `BD_DATASET_ACTIVITY` — Recent activity / post history
- `BD_DATASET_PROFILES` — Profile data
- `BD_DATASET_WEB_SCRAPER` — Generic web page scraping

---

## Known Issues & Limitations

### Reliability
- **Activity check failures are common** — Bright Data's activity API frequently times out or returns no datable posts, causing leads to land in `ACTIVITY_FAILED`. The retry logic (5 × 10s outer, 2 × 5s inner, 120s timeout) mitigates but doesn't eliminate this
- **LinkedIn rate limiting** — Direct scraping of contact overlays is throttled by LinkedIn (HTTP 429/999). Exponential backoff + jitter helps, but large batches will slow down significantly
- **`li_at` cookie expiry** — The LinkedIn session cookie must be manually refreshed from a browser whenever it expires (no automated auth flow)

### Data Quality
- **First name extraction** can pick up the *viewer's* name from embedded JSON instead of the profile owner's. Mitigated by prioritizing `<title>` and `og:title` over JSON, but edge cases remain
- **Deep web crawl is shallow** — Only crawls up to 5 internal pages from the lead's personal website; won't find emails on deeply nested pages
- **Email validation is heuristic** — Uses blocklists and regex rather than SMTP verification; false negatives possible for unusual TLDs or domains

### Architecture
- **No database** — All state is stored in JSON files in the `progress/` directory. Not suitable for multi-user or cloud deployment without modification
- **Sequential processing** — Leads are processed one at a time. No parallelism or queue system
- **Single-machine only** — The filesystem-based persistence and in-memory state make this a local-only tool
- **Large monolithic files** — [scraper-actions.ts](file:///c:/Users/mimod/OneDrive/Desktop/Projects/leads_qualiferV2/src/app/actions/scraper-actions.ts) (1428 lines) and [Dashboard.tsx](file:///c:/Users/mimod/OneDrive/Desktop/Projects/leads_qualiferV2/src/components/Dashboard.tsx) (1001 lines) concentrate most logic in two files
- **Debug logging left in** — Verbose `console.log` statements (including `[DEBUG]` blocks) remain throughout the activity checking code
